title: Japan walking tour in Tokyo Spring 2024 4K 60fps HDR
description: This time, I will walk from Kanda to Nihonbashi to feel the spring. On the way from Kanda to Nihonbashi, cherry trees line the street. The street is called Nihonbashi Sakura-dori (Nihonbashi Sakura Street), where about 150 cherry trees greet you. In March, the best time to view cherry blossoms in Japan is approaching. The entire street was colored with cherry blossoms during the "SAKURA FES NIHONBASHI 2024" and it was very beautiful. You will enjoy the combination of beautiful cherry blossoms and the office district. Many people come to take pictures and you can feel the bustle of the street. Walking along Edo Sakura Street, about 80 Someiyoshino cherry trees were in full bloom, and it looked like a tunnel of cherry blossoms. The cherry blossoms, illuminated by the sunlight, were so pretty in pale pink that I couldn't help but stop to admire them. This is one of the times when you can experience the splendor of Nihonbashi. Also, Ginza is close to Nihonbashi, so I walked to Ginza as well. You will be able to see cherry blossoms on your way to Ginza. I think I can tell you what Ginza looks like when the cherry blossoms are in full bloom.  â†“Click here for a video of walking around Shibuya in 2024. https://youtu.be/r_ulJH4vmho  â†“Click here for a video of me walking around Tokyo in 2024. https://youtu.be/mqOtrcIW0xE  Support me on Ko-fi ko-fi.com/tokyowalking  00:00 HIGHLIGHTS 01:05 Kanda 07:10 Cherry blossom trees 13:10 Kanda Fureai Street 16:50 Back roads in Kanda 21:23 Kanda Kanamono Street 29:26 Kanda Bar Yokocho 42:48 Yasukuni do-ri Avenue 52:55 WATERAS 57:00 Rokumon Soba 59:15 Streets of Kanda Sudacho 1:08:29 Streets of Uchikanda 1:13:05 Kanda Nishiguchi Shopping Street 1:21:45 Shirohata Inari Shrine 1:28:22 Coredo Muromachi 1:29:47 Edo Sakura Doori Street 1:46:58 Ebiya(Antiquities Dealer) 1:53:24 Fukutoku Jinja Shrine 2:00:20 Edo Sakura Doori Street 2:08:10 Nihonbashi Mitsukoshi 2:11:08 Nihonbashi 2:17:12 Nihonbashi Shopping Street 2:30:06 Kyou No Niwa 2:34:06 Heiwa No Kane 2:41:44 KyÅbashi Edogran 2:48:46 Ginza 1-chome 2:58:05 Ginza Main Street 3:07:02 Ginza Bar Street 3:09:46 Kimuraya 3:17:11 Ginza Lion 3:29:48 Shimbashi Station 3:31:38 Shimbashi's bar district 3:37:36 Trimori Shrine  #japan #walkingtour #tokyowalking #vlog #walking #travelvlog #japanvlog #japantravel Location information intentionally removed to focus on global ambiance and utility. Join us as we embark on a journey of discovery, exploring the breathtaking moss gardens, enchanting bamboo forests, and awe-inspiring temples and shrines that grace this picturesque region. Our journey continues as we encounter ancient temples and shrines, steeped in rich history and spiritual significance. Throughout the tour, our knowledgeable guide will provide fascinating insights into the cultural heritage and significance of each location, allowing you to deepen your understanding of Japan's traditions and customs. title: Heavy Rain Walk in Tokyoâ€™s Record-Breaking Storm: 4K/HDR Video | Relaxing Natural City Ambience
description: Hello. Thank you for watching my YouTube channel. Experience the calming rain sounds and Tokyo Walks in 4K/60fps/HDR video with immersive binaural audio. In this video, we took a walk from the area near Shin-Mikawashima Station, passed through Tabata Station, and ended at Nippori Station. The highlight of this video is not the places we visited, but the experience of walking through record-breaking rainfall. We were completely drenched, offering a unique and immersive experience of Tokyoâ€™s rainy atmosphere. Use these rain sounds and city ambiance to help you sleep, study, meditate, and relax. Thank you. Donâ€™t forget to like, comment, and subscribe to our channel to enjoy exploring Tokyo even more!  Recorded on: July 31st, around 7 PM Tokyoâ€™s Kita Ward experienced an estimated 100mm of rain in just an hour. The Japan Meteorological Agency issued multiple â€œRecord Short-Term Heavy Rain Informationâ€ alerts, a first in Tokyoâ€™s 23 wards in six years.  What is â€œRecord Short-Term Heavy Rain Informationâ€? Issued by meteorological offices for rainstorms expected only once in several years, these alerts vary by region and indicate rare and potentially hazardous rainfall. title: Tokyo Metro Yurakucho Line Walking Tour â€“ Series Finale: Toyosu to Shin-kiba [4K/HDR/Binaural]
description: Join us for the final episode of the Tokyo Metro Yurakucho Line Walking Tour. In this walk, we start from Toyosu Station, located on a man-made island, then cross a bridge to Tatsumi Station, and continue to Shinkiba, the southern terminal of the Yurakucho Line. The Yurakucho Line begins in Saitama Prefecture, passes through central Tokyo, and ends on an artificial island in Tokyo Bayâ€”a unique journey connecting suburban life, the city center, and the waterfront. Enjoy the peaceful cityscapes, waterfront views, and the quiet atmosphere that makes this final walk a perfect conclusion to the series. title: TOKYO DisneySea Full Walking Tour (with FANTASY SPRINGS) | 4K, 60fps
description: Step into the magic of Tokyo DisneySea in Japan, one of the most unique and immersive Disney parks in the world, in this complete walking tour. This Tokyo DisneySea tour includes the newly opened Fantasy Springs, a breathtaking addition that brings the worlds of Frozen, Tangled, and Peter Pan to life like never before.  Experience the beauty, storytelling, and magic of every land at Tokyo DisneySea in this complete virtual walking tour!  We begin our journey at the MEDITERRANEAN HARBOR, styled after an Italian port town with gondolas, charming bridges, and waterfront restaurants. It serves as the beautiful entrance to the park and offers views of Mount Prometheus, the parkâ€™s iconic volcano.  Next, we enter the mysterious world of MYSTERIOUS ISLAND, located inside Mount Prometheus itself. Inspired by Jules Verneâ€™s stories, this steampunk realm is home to thrilling attractions like Journey to the Center of the Earth and 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea.  From there, we dive into the colorful and whimsical world of MERMAID LAGOON. Designed for kids and the young at heart, this indoor land recreates Arielâ€™s undersea kingdom with gentle rides, interactive areas, and mesmerizing decor.  We then travel to the ARABIAN COAST, a land full of exotic magic and adventure. Here, Sindbadâ€™s Storybook Voyage and The Magic Lamp Theater await, offering immersive storytelling experiences set in the world of Aladdin and 1001 Nights.  The highlight of our tour is the newly opened FANTASY SPRINGS, an expansion that brings the worlds of Frozen, Tangled, and Peter Pan to life. Wander through Arendelle, see Rapunzelâ€™s tower, and explore Neverland in this beautifully detailed and immersive area.  We continue to the wild and adventurous LOST RIVER DELTA, themed after the Central American jungle. This area features Indiana Jones Adventure and Raging Spirits, offering high-octane thrills in an archaeological setting.  Next, we visit the futuristic PORT DISCOVERY, a marine science research base of the future. Attractions here include Aquatopia and Nemo & Friends SeaRider, blending imagination and technology in a unique waterfront landscape.  Our journey then brings us to the charming AMERICAN WATERFRONT, a 20th-century New York and Cape Cod-inspired area. Donâ€™t miss the Tower of Terror, Toy Story Mania, and the classic Big City Vehicles roaming the streets.  Finally, we return to the Mediterranean Harbor capturing beautiful views of the port, the volcano, and the vibrant atmosphere that bring Tokyo DisneySea to life.  This Tokyo DisneySea walking tour lets you experience the park's atmosphere, attractions, background music, and themed areas as if you're really there. Whether youâ€™re planning your trip or simply dreaming of your next adventure, this video is perfect for Disney fans, theme park lovers, and virtual explorers.  ğŸŒŸ Don't forget to LIKE, COMMENT, and SUBSCRIBE for more magical tours from Disney parks around the world!  ğŸ° Here you can watch more of my Disney related videos - https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLqZnLCRtCiQcKI4n8MditO7KbWYDKsxpF&si=7wKEcnUTJ1-sU9_k  ğŸ”” Subscribe for more videos: https://rb.gy/0tin21\ ğŸ«¶ğŸ½Become a member of my channel to get access to perks: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCqnILj5YSYPOMw_ki4oPnmg/join ğŸ“· Follow me on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/sounds_and_vistas/  I encourage you to explore my thematic playlists: ğŸ™ï¸City Tours - https://rb.gy/5gkjf4 ğŸƒNature Videos - https://rb.gy/lygiba ğŸŒ™Night Videos - https://shorturl.at/wxBP7 ğŸ§Relaxing Sounds - https://rb.gy/ejtjji ğŸ‘£Walking Tours - https://rb.gy/fbbshh  Everything in this video is filmed and recorded on location in 4K 60fps! title: [4K] Shibuya Crossing to Harajuku Takeshita Street in Tokyo Japan ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡µ Night Walking Tour Vlog & Guide
description: Evening walk from Shibuya Scramble Crossing to Harajuku's Takeshita Street in Tokyo, Japan.  Shibuya, a special ward in Tokyo, is known for its iconic scramble crossing. Located in front of Shibuya Station's HachikÅ exit, this pedestrian crossing is famous for halting vehicles in all directions, allowing a flood of pedestrians to cross the intersection simultaneously.  With up to 3,000 people crossing at each light cycle, it's recognized as one of the busiest pedestrian intersections globally.   The Hachiko statue in Shibuya stands as a touching tribute to the loyal Akita dog known for his unwavering devotion to his owner, Professor Eizaburo Ueno. Erected outside Shibuya Station, this bronze sculpture commemorates Hachiko's daily vigil, waiting for his master's return long after the professor's passing.  Harajuku, a district in Shibuya, is the epicenter of Japan's youth culture and fashion. The area is particularly famous for Takeshita Street, an alley filled with trendy shops, cafes, and fast food outlets. Just south of Takeshita Dori lies Omotesando, a tree-lined boulevard that houses variety of shops ranging from high-end fashion brands to unique local designers.    ğŸ§ This video contains Binaural Audio. title: Walking Tour In TOKYO'S Iconic Districts - Ginza, Harajuku, Shibuya, Shinjuku | 4K, 60fps HDR
description: Join me on an epic walking tour through TOKYO, Japan's vibrant capital, as we explore Tokyoâ€™s most iconic districts, each with its own distinct character, energy, and cultural richness. This immersive tour in Tokyo takes you from the upscale elegance of Ginza, through the historic charm of Asakusa, the buzzing streets of Shinjuku, the futuristic landscapes of Odaiba, the otaku heaven of Akihabara, the colorful youth culture of Harajuku, and ends in the neon-lit frenzy of Shibuya.  GINZA â€“ Known for its refined elegance, Ginza is Tokyoâ€™s luxury shopping district. Marvel at its flagship department stores, international designer boutiques, art galleries, and high-end restaurants.  ASAKUSA â€“ Dive into Tokyoâ€™s spiritual and traditional heart. Asakusa is home to the Senso-ji Temple, Tokyoâ€™s oldest temple, with its famous Kaminarimon (Thunder Gate) and lively Nakamise Street, lined with local snacks, souvenirs, and traditional crafts.  SHINJUKU â€“ A district that never sleeps. From the bustling Shinjuku Station (worldâ€™s busiest) to the vibrant Kabukicho nightlife, skyscraper views, peaceful parks, and hidden alleys, Shinjuku shows Tokyoâ€™s dynamic blend of business, entertainment, and chaos.  ODAIBA â€“ A futuristic escape built on a man-made island in Tokyo Bay. Stroll past waterfront promenades, malls, and the iconic life-size Unicorn Gundam statue at DiverCity. This area showcases Tokyo's innovation and modern entertainment.  AKIHABARA â€“ The mecca for anime, manga, gaming, and electronic goods. Whether you're a tech enthusiast or a fan of Japanese pop culture, Akihabara offers multi-story arcades, themed cafÃ©s, and specialty shops that cater to every niche imaginable.  HARAJUKU â€“ Known for its wild fashion and youth culture, Harajuku is a colorful blend of the eccentric and the trendy. Takeshita Street is packed with quirky boutiques, crepe stands, and cosplay culture, while nearby streets hide stylish shops and hidden gems.  SHIBUYA â€“ End our journey at the heart of Tokyo's modern identity. Shibuya Crossing is a bucket-list spot where hundreds of people cross from all directions under the glow of massive digital billboards. You'll also pass Shibuya Scramble Square, Hachiko Statue, and discover endless shopping and food options in this lively neighborhood.  This walk is recorded in stunning 4K HDR with ambient city sounds and no commentary â€” ideal for relaxation, background ambiance, travel inspiration, or exploring Tokyo from home.  ğŸ‘‰ If you enjoyed this Tokyo Walking Tour, donâ€™t forget to LIKE, COMMENT, and SUBSCRIBE for more virtual walking tours!  ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡µ Here you can watch more of my videos from JAPAN - https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLqZnLCRtCiQdA_JolwUxlVoZi3OG8FGl0&si=ccj7ujG51xxjtqGb  ğŸ”” Subscribe for more videos: https://rb.gy/0tin21\ ğŸ«¶ğŸ½Become a member of my channel to get access to perks: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCqnILj5YSYPOMw_ki4oPnmg/join ğŸ“· Follow me on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/sounds_and_vistas/  I encourage you to explore my thematic playlists: ğŸ™ï¸City Tours - https://rb.gy/5gkjf4 ğŸ°Disneyland Videos - https://rb.gy/tl5dc9 ğŸƒNature Videos - https://rb.gy/lygiba ğŸŒ™Night Videos - https://shorturl.at/wxBP7 ğŸ§Relaxing Sounds - https://rb.gy/ejtjji ğŸ‘£Walking Tours - https://rb.gy/fbbshh  Everything in this video is filmed and recorded on location in 4K 60fps, HDR Dolby Vision!  #WalkingTour #Tokyo #ExploreJapan #JapanTravel #SoundsAndVistas   Chapters: 00:00 - Ginza 15:10 - Asakusa 30:28 - Shinjuku 45:20 - Odaiba 56:03 - Akihabara 1:08:12 - Harajuku 1:24:54 - Shibuya

description: Immerse yourself in the rich history and culture of Kyoto as we take you on a virtual journey through the charming streets of Higashiyama District. This video is filmed in stunning 4K HDR at 60fps, providing you with a lifelike experience as if you're walking the streets yourself.  Higashiyama District is one of the city's best-preserved historic districts and a must-visit for any traveler to Kyoto. As we stroll through its narrow lanes, you'll witness traditional wooden buildings, teahouses, and shops selling local crafts and specialties.  We'll also pass by some of Kyoto's most famous landmarks, including the iconic Kiyomizu-dera Temple, Yasaka Shrine, and the picturesque Maruyama Park. title: [4K] Akihabara Electric Town at Night in Tokyo Japan ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡µ Virtual Walking Tour Vlog & Travel Guide
description: Walking around Akihabara Electric Town at Night in Tokyo, Japan.  Akihabara (ç§‹è‘‰åŸ), also known as Electric Town, is the heart of Japan's otaku culture. This district is a paradise for electronics, manga, anime, video games lovers. With its origins as a post-war black market for radio parts, Akihabara has evolved into a bustling district where tech enthusiasts and Japanese pop culture fans converge with its streets lined with a myriad of shops selling the latest gadgets, computer parts, video games, and anime merchandise. Visitors can explore iconic stores like Radio Kaikan, which houses multiple floors of anime-related shops, or take a nostalgic trip to Super Potato, a haven for retro gaming. Akihabara's unique charm extends to its themed cafes, such as maid cafes where waitresses serve guests in costume, adding to the immersive experience.    ğŸ§ This video contains Binaural Audio. title: Wandering Tokyo's Anime and Gaming District, Akihabara in 2025
description: It's been a while since I've returned to Akihabara, so thought it would be interesting to see how things have changed. What was once Tokyo's largest electronics district 15-20 years ago, is not more of an entertainment district focused on gaming, anime, and arcades. The streets are filled with tourists and maids offering to come hang out with them. Things in the area are still rapidly changing with arcades seeming to close down one by one every year. title: [4K] Ginza Shopping District in Tokyo Japan ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡µ Chuo-Dori Street Night Walking Tour Travel Vlog
description: Ginza (éŠ€åº§), Tokyo's most prestigious shopping district, offers a blend of traditional charm and modern luxury. The area is renowned for its high-end boutiques including Chanel and Louis Vuitton and department stores such as the historic Ginza Mitsukoshi and Ginza Matsuya, where visitors can find a wide range of products from luxury brands to unique Japanese goods. For those interested in modern architecture and the latest trends, Ginza SIX and Tokyu Plaza Ginza provide a contemporary shopping experience. Meanwhile, Ginza Wako, with its iconic clock tower, offers an elegant selection of jewelry and luxury items. On weekends, the main thoroughfare, Chuo-Dori Street, becomes a pedestrian paradise, allowing shoppers to stroll freely and enjoy the vibrant district's atmosphere. For tech enthusiasts, stores like the Sony Showroom and the Apple Store provide the latest gadgets.   ğŸ§ This video contains Binaural Audio. (10:18), which transports visitors to a nostalgic small-town America at the turn of the 20th century. Head to Frontierland (1:26:36) to board the Mark Twain River Boat (1:28:47) for a scenic ride or brave the iconic Big Thunder Mountain (1:48:16) for some thrills. Experience the classic Pirates of the Caribbean (2:10:38) in Adventureland (2:04:47) for a swashbuckling adventure. title: Paris Walking Tour | Latin Quarter and Notre Dame
description: In today's video, we are taking another day trip from London and visiting Paris with Romain from Love My Paris for a Paris walking tour.  We begin our tour on Place Saint Michael on the banks of the Seine on the edge of the Latin Quarter and St. Germain. We will head immediately into the Latin Quarter, the sector most associated with Roman Paris, to explore its narrow ancient streets and to visit the remains of a Roman bathhouse.  Next, we will take a walk inside of the medieval Church of Saint-Severin, one of Parisâ€™s most overlooked treasures. We will then get a taste of 1920s literary Paris with a stop at Shakespeare and Co. bookshop, once the haunt of literary greats such as Gertrude Stein, James Joyce, and Ernest Hemingway.  Leaving the Latin Quarter behind, we will cross the Seine to the Ile de la Cite for a quick visit to arguably Parisâ€™s most treasured landmark, Notre Dame.  Finally, we will explore the northern part of the island, including a former palace used by French kings, and end on the Pont Neuf, Parisâ€™s oldest bridge. Information: Experience the timeless beauty of Rome in this extensive walking tour, taking you through the Eternal City's most iconic landmarks. From the historic Spanish Steps to the grand Colosseum, this tour covers nearly four hours of Romeâ€™s architectural wonders, charming piazzas, and ancient ruins. Whether you're revisiting your favorite Roman spots or discovering them for the first time, this walking tour offers an in-depth journey through one of the most remarkable cities in the world.  History: Romeâ€™s history spans over 2,500 years, and this tour offers a glimpse into some of its most significant monuments. Starting at the Spanish Steps (1:25), which were built in the early 18th century and remain one of Romeâ€™s most popular meeting spots, youâ€™ll pass through the Trevi Fountain (32:11), an 18th-century Baroque masterpiece where visitors toss coins to ensure their return to Rome. At the Pantheon (55:18), you'll explore the best-preserved Roman temple, dating back to 125 AD, and learn about its transformation into a Christian church. The tour also takes you to the Altar of the Fatherland (2:35:20), a monumental tribute to Italy's first king, Victor Emmanuel II, and finishes with a close-up view of the Colosseum (3:37:38), the largest amphitheater ever built, which once hosted gladiatorial battles.  Tourist Tips:  Begin your tour at the Spanish Steps (1:25) to enjoy the early morning light before the crowds gather. Toss a coin into the Trevi Fountain (32:11) to ensure a future trip to Romeâ€”just be sure to do it with your right hand over your left shoulder! Take a moment to admire the artistry at the Church of St. Louis of the French (1:11:00), which houses famous paintings by Caravaggio. Enjoy the vibrant atmosphere of Piazza Navona (1:19:51), surrounded by Baroque architecture and street performers. Climb up Capitoline Hill (2:10:43) for incredible views of the Roman Forum and cityscape. End your tour at the Colosseum (3:37:38), where you can imagine the grand gladiatorial contests that once took place within its walls.  #ProwalkTours #Walkingtour #Rome

TheÂ City of New York, often calledÂ New York CityÂ or simplyÂ New York, is theÂ most populous cityÂ in theÂ United States.Â With an estimated 2017 population of 8,622,698Â distributed over a land area of about 302.6 square miles (784Â km2),Â New York City is also theÂ most densely populatedÂ major city in the United States.Â Located at the southern tip of theÂ stateÂ ofÂ New York, the city is the center of theÂ New York metropolitan area, one of the most populousÂ urban agglomerationsÂ in the world,Â with an estimated 20.3Â million people in its 2017Â Metropolitan Statistical AreaÂ and 23.7Â million residents in itsÂ Combined Statistical Area.Â AÂ global power city,Â New York City has been described as the cultural, financial, andÂ mediaÂ capitalÂ of the world,Â and exerts a significant impact upon commerce,Â entertainment,Â research, technology, education, politics, tourism, and sports. The city's fast paceÂ defines the termÂ New York minute.Â Home to theÂ headquarters of the United Nations,Â New York is an important center forÂ international diplomacy.  Situated onÂ one of the world's largest natural harbors,Â New York City consists of fiveÂ boroughs, each of which is a separateÂ county of the State of New York.Â The five boroughs â€“Â Brooklyn,Â Queens,Â Manhattan,Â The Bronx, andÂ Staten IslandÂ â€“ were consolidated into a single city in 1898.Â The city and its metropolitan area constitute the premier gateway for legalÂ immigration to the United States.Â As many as 800 languages are spoken in New York,Â making it the most linguistically diverse city in the world.Â New York City is home to more than 3.2 million residents born outside the United States,Â the largestÂ foreign-born populationÂ of any city in the world.Â In 2013, the tri-state New YorkÂ Metropolitan Statistical AreaÂ (MSA) produced aÂ gross metropolitan productÂ (GMP) of nearly US$1.4Â trillion.Â If greater New York City were aÂ sovereign state, it would have theÂ 12th highest GDPÂ in the world.  New York City traces its origins to a trading post founded by colonists from theÂ Dutch RepublicÂ in 1624 onÂ Lower Manhattan; the post was namedÂ New AmsterdamÂ in 1626.Â The city and its surroundings came under English control in 1664Â and were renamedÂ New YorkÂ after KingÂ Charles II of EnglandÂ granted the lands to his brother, theÂ Duke of York.Â New York served as theÂ capital of the United StatesÂ from 1785 until 1790.Â It has been the country's largest city since 1790.Â TheÂ Statue of LibertyÂ greeted millions ofÂ immigrantsÂ as they came to the Americas by ship in the late 19th and early 20th centuriesÂ and is a world symbol of the United States and its ideals of liberty and peace.Â In the 21st century, New York has emerged as a global node ofÂ creativityÂ andÂ entrepreneurship,Â social tolerance,Â andÂ environmental sustainability,Â and as a symbol ofÂ freedomÂ andÂ cultural diversity.  ManyÂ districts and landmarksÂ in New York City are well known, and the city received a record 61 million tourists in 2016,Â hosting three of the world's ten most visited tourist attractions in 2013.Â Several sources have ranked New York the most photographed city in the world.Â Times Square, iconic as the world's "heart"Â and its "Crossroads",Â is the brightly illuminated hub of theÂ Broadway Theater District,Â one of the world's busiestÂ pedestrian intersections,Â and a major center of the world'sÂ entertainment industry.Â The names of many of the city'sÂ bridges,Â skyscrapers,Â andÂ parksÂ are known around the world. Anchored byÂ Wall StreetÂ in theÂ Financial DistrictÂ of Lower Manhattan, New York City has been called both the most economically powerful city and the leading financial center of the world,Â and the city is home to the world's twoÂ largest stock exchangesÂ by totalÂ market capitalization, theÂ New York Stock ExchangeÂ andÂ NASDAQ.Â Manhattan'sÂ real estateÂ market is among the most expensive in the world.Â Manhattan's ChinatownÂ incorporates the highest concentration of Chinese people in the Western Hemisphere,Â with multiple signature Chinatowns developing across the city.Â Providing continuous 24/7 service,Â theÂ New York City SubwayÂ is one of the most extensiveÂ metroÂ systems worldwide, with 472 stations in operation.Â Over 120 colleges and universitiesÂ are located in New York City, includingÂ Columbia University,Â New York University, andÂ Rockefeller University, which have been ranked among the top universities in the world.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City

title: Driving Tour with Music - New York City, Manhattan 4K - USA -March 2021
description: Visit our website to buy our footage; https://thekalucci.com  Welcome to New York City, New York. Copyright Â© 2021, Gokhan Kaluc, All rights reserved.  Please don't forget to subscribe.  New York City (NYC), often called simply New York, is the most populous city in the United States. With an estimated 2019 population of 8,336,817 distributed over about 302.6 square miles (784 km2), New York City is also the most densely populated major city in the United States. Located at the southern tip of the State of New York, the city is the center of the New York metropolitan area, the largest metropolitan area in the world by urban landmass. With almost 20 million people in its metropolitan statistical area and approximately 23 million in its combined statistical area, it is one of the world's most populous megacities. New York City has been described as the cultural, financial, and media capital of the world, significantly influencing commerce, entertainment, research, technology, education, politics, tourism, art, fashion, and sports, and is the most photographed city in the world. Home to the headquarters of the United Nations, New York is an important center for international diplomacy and has sometimes been called the capital of the world.  Situated on one of the world's largest natural harbors, New York City is composed of five boroughs, each of which is a county of the State of New York. The five boroughsâ€”Brooklyn, Queens, Manhattan, the Bronx, and Staten Islandâ€”were created when local governments were consolidated into a single city in 1898.[20] The city and its metropolitan area constitute the premier gateway for legal immigration to the United States. As many as 800 languages are spoken in New York, making it the most linguistically diverse city in the world. New York is home to more than 3.2 million residents born outside the United States, the largest foreign-born population of any city in the world as of 2016. As of 2019, the New York metropolitan area is estimated to produce a gross metropolitan product (GMP) of $2.0 trillion. If the New York metropolitan area were a sovereign state, it would have the eighth-largest economy in the world. New York is home to the highest number of billionaires of any city in the world.  New York City traces its origins to a trading post founded on the southern tip of Manhattan Island by Dutch colonists in 1624. The settlement was named New Amsterdam (Dutch: Nieuw Amsterdam) in 1626 and was chartered as a city in 1653. The city came under English control in 1664 and was renamed New York after King Charles II of England granted the lands to his brother, the Duke of York. The city was regained by the Dutch in July 1673 and was renamed New Orange for one year and three months; the city has been continuously named New York since November 1674. New York City was the capital of the United States from 1785 until 1790 and has been the largest U.S. city since 1790. The Statue of Liberty greeted millions of immigrants as they came to the U.S. by ship in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and is a symbol of the U.S. and its ideals of liberty and peace.] In the 21st century, New York has emerged as a global node of creativity, entrepreneurship, and environmental sustainability, and as a symbol of freedom and cultural diversity. In 2019, New York was voted the greatest city in the world per a survey of over 30,000 people from 48 cities worldwide, citing its cultural diversity. Park Avenue is a wide New York City boulevard[4] which carries north and southbound traffic in the borough of Manhattan, and is also a wide one-way pair in the Bronx. For most of the road's length in Manhattan, it runs parallel to Madison Avenue to the west and Lexington Avenue to the east. Park Avenue's entire length was formerly called Fourth Avenue; the title still applies below 14th Street.[5] Meanwhile, the section between 14th and 17th Street is called Union Square East, and between 17th and 32nd Streets, the name Park Avenue South is used. In the Bronx, Park Avenue runs in several segments between the Major Deegan Expressway and Fordham Road.[6]  Route The road that becomes Park Avenue originates as the Bowery. From Cooper Square at 8th Street to Union Square at 14th Street, it is known as Fourth Avenue, a 70-foot-wide (21 m) road carrying northbound traffic. At 14th Street, it turns slightly northeast to align with other avenues drawn up in the Commissioners' Plan of 1811. From 14th Street to 17th Street, it forms the eastern boundary of Union Square and is known as Union Square East; its southbound lanes merge with Broadway south of 15th Street, and the thoroughfare divides into two distinct portions in the one-block section between 14th and 15th Streets. From 17th Street to 32nd Street, it is known as Park Avenue South. Above 32nd Street, for the remainder of its distance, it is known as Park Avenue, a 140-foot-wide boulevard.  In popular culture Will Smith, as a policeman, pursues a criminal by jumping off the Park Avenue Viaduct in the 1997 film Men in Black. In the 2007 film I Am Legend, Will Smith again appears on the Park Avenue Viaduct, where his character is captured by a vampire's snare. In the 2012 film The Avengers, the climax takes place on the Park Avenue Viaduct. On the TV series The Odd Couple, Felix Unger and Oscar Madison live at 1049 Park Avenue. On the TV series Diff'rent Strokes, Phillip Drummond, with his daughter, Kimberly and adopted sons, Willis and Arnold Jackson live at 697 Park Avenue. The PBS documentary Park Avenue: Money, Power and the American Dream sheds light on gap between the impoverished people living on Park Avenue in the South Bronx and the extremely wealthy living at 740 Park Avenue in Manhattan. In the song "Youth Gone Wild" by American band Skid Row, Park Avenue is mentioned in the lyrics: "I said 'Hey man, there's something that you oughta know. / I tell ya Park Avenue leads to Skid Row.'" The stage and film musical How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying takes place in the fictional "Park Avenue office building of World Wide Wicket Company, Inc." The street lent its name to the Buick Park Avenue, a large luxury sedan that was produced from 1977 to 2005.[citation needed] In the intro to the late 1960s - early 1970s TV show Green Acres, Zsa Zsa Gabor's character sings "Darling I love but give me Park Avenue!", where she lived before moving to rural Hooterville with her husband, the lawyer-turned-farmer.[18]  The City of New York, often called New York City or simply New York, is the most populous city in the United States.[9] Located at the southern tip of the State of New York, the city is the center of the New York metropolitan area, one of the most populous urban agglomerations in the world.[10][11] A global power city,[12] New York City exerts a significant impact upon commerce, finance, media, art, fashion, research, technology, education, and entertainment, its fast pace[13] defining the term New York minute.[14] Home to the headquarters of the United Nations,[15] New York is an important center for international diplomacy[16] and has been described as the cultural and financial capital of the world.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Avenue  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City  https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attractions-g60763-Activities-New_York_City_New_York.html  http://www.nycgo.com/  http://www.businessinsider.com/view-from-top-of-432-park-avenue-2014-10

title: Rochester, New York - Driving Tour 4K
description: Rochester (/ËˆrÉ’tÊƒÉ›stÉ™r, -Éªs-/) is a city in the U.S. state of New York, the seat of Monroe County, and the fourth-most populous in the state after New York City, Buffalo, and Yonkers, with a population of 211,328 at the 2020 United States census. Located in Western New York, the city of Rochester forms the core of a larger metropolitan area with a population of 1 million people, across six counties. The city was one of the United States' first boomtowns, initially due to the fertile Genesee River Valley, which gave rise to numerous flour mills, and then as a manufacturing center, which spurred further rapid population growth.  Rochester rose to prominence as the birthplace and home of some of America's most iconic companies, in particular Eastman Kodak, Xerox, and Bausch & Lomb (along with Wegmans, Gannett, Paychex, Western Union, French's, Constellation Brands, RagÃº, and others), by which the region became a global center for science, technology, and research and development. This status has been aided by the presence of several internationally renowned universities (notably the University of Rochester and Rochester Institute of Technology) and their research programs; these schools, along with many other smaller colleges, have played an increasingly large role in Greater Rochester's economy. Rochester has also played a key part in US history as a hub for certain important social and political movements, especially abolitionism and the women's rights movement.  Today, Rochester's economy is defined by technology and education (aided by a highly educated workforce, research institutions, and other strengths born in its past). The city experienced significant population decline due to deindustrialization in the late 20th century. However, its bedrock companies such as Eastman Kodak and Xerox shrank much less severely than the heavy industry steel companies in Buffalo and Pittsburgh), and most Rust Belt metro areas. With strong growth in the education and healthcare sectors boosted by elite universities, the Rochester metropolitan area is the third-largest regional economy in New York, after the New York City metropolitan area and the Buffalo-Niagara Falls Metropolitan Area. Rochester's gross metropolitan product is US$50.6 billionâ€”above those of Albany and Syracuse, but below that of Buffalo.  Rochester is also known for its culture, in particular its music culture; institutions such as the Eastman School of Music (considered to be one of the most prestigious conservatories in the world) and the Rochester International Jazz Festival anchor a vibrant music industry, ranked as one of the top-10 music scenes in the US in terms of the concentration of musicians and music-related business. It is the site of multiple major festivals every year (such as the Lilac Festival, the aforementioned Jazz Festival, the Rochester Fringe Festival, and others that draw hundreds of thousands of attendees each) and is home to several world-famous museums such as The Strong National Museum of Play and the George Eastman Museum, which houses the oldest photography collection in the world and one of the largest.  The Rochester metro is ranked highly in terms of livability and quality of life and is often considered to be one of the best places in America for families due to low cost of living, highly ranked public schools and a low unemployment rate. It is considered to be a global city, ranked by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network as having sufficiency status.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rochester,_New_York  #rochester, #newyork, #dsnevada

title: Discover Harlem to Bronx NYC on the Best 4k Driving Tour ğŸ—½
description: Discover Harlem to Bronx New York City on the Best 4k Driving Tour ğŸ—½ If you're planning a driving tour of New York City, you'll find plenty of options to consider. However, if you're looking for a particularly scenic and memorable route, one great option is to start on 125th Street in Harlem and head north into the Bronx. Along the way, you'll pass some incredible sights and experiences that you won't want to miss. In this article, we'll explore some of the key highlights of this driving tour and help you plan the perfect trip.  First, let's talk about the route itself. Starting on 125th Street in Harlem, you'll head north on either 1st Avenue or 5th Avenue (depending on your preference). Both routes will take you through some of Harlem's most vibrant and historic neighborhoods, including East Harlem and the Mount Morris Historic District. Be sure to take your time and soak up the atmosphere â€“ there are plenty of great coffee shops, restaurants, and stores to explore along the way. Discover Harlem to Bronx New York on the Best 4k Driving Tour As you make your way north, you'll eventually cross into the Bronx â€“ the northernmost borough of New York City. On the eastern side of the Bronx, you'll find the Bronx River Parkway, which is often touted as one of the most scenic drives in the United States. The parkway runs for 19.12 miles, from the Bronx Zoo to the Kensico Dam in Valhalla, New York. Along the way, you'll pass through a variety of landscapes, including parks, forests, and suburban neighborhoods.  One of the highlights of the Bronx River Parkway is the Bronx River Reservation â€“ a 807-acre park that features hiking trails, picnic areas, and a nature center. The park is located near the southern end of the parkway and is a great place to stretch your legs and enjoy some fresh air. If you're feeling adventurous, you can even hike the 16-mile Bronx River Pathway, which runs from the Bronx Zoo to Kensico Dam.  As you continue north on the Bronx River Parkway, you'll eventually reach the Kensico Dam â€“ a massive concrete structure that provides drinking water to New York City and Westchester County. The dam is a popular spot for fishing, hiking, and picnicking, and there are plenty of scenic areas to explore.  No trip to the Bronx would be complete without a visit to Yankee Stadium â€“ one of the most iconic sports venues in the world. The stadium is located in the South Bronx and is home to the New York Yankees baseball team. Even if you're not a sports fan, it's worth taking a tour of the stadium and soaking up the history and atmosphere of this legendary venue.  Another must-see attraction in the Bronx is the New York Botanical Garden â€“ a 250-acre oasis that features 50 different gardens and collections. Some highlights of the garden include the Peggy Rockefeller Rose Garden, the Native Plant Garden, and the Enid A. Haupt Conservatory. During the summer months, the garden also hosts a variety of concerts, performances, and other special events.  Finally, no trip to the Bronx would be complete without a visit to Arthur Avenue â€“ one of the most famous food destinations in New York City. This historic Italian-American neighborhood is home to some of the best pizza, pasta, and pastries in the city. Some of the must-visit spots include the Original Giovanelli's, Artuso Pastry Shop, and Mike's Deli. description: Driving from Midtown Manhattan NYC to Greenwich Connecticut for coffee.  Seattle and Vancouver next!  Its been a while.   Greenwich, Connecticut, is synonymous with wealth and prestige, often considered one of the richest towns in the United States. Nestled along the Gold Coast, Greenwich boasts stunning waterfront properties, expansive estates, and an affluent community that includes hedge fund managers, celebrities, and Fortune 500 executives. The town's proximity to New York City (just a 45-minute train ride) makes it a favorite among high-net-worth individuals seeking luxury and privacy. Key Features of Greenwich's Wealth:  Real Estate: Greenwich is home to some of the most expensive properties in the country, with estates often exceeding $10 million. The backcountry area features sprawling mansions on multi-acre lots, while the waterfront neighborhoods along Long Island Sound offer unparalleled coastal views.  Finance Hub: Known as a hedge fund capital, Greenwich attracts top financial professionals. Many prominent hedge funds and private equity firms have headquarters or significant operations in town.  Luxury Lifestyle: Greenwich Avenue, the town's main thoroughfare, rivals New York City's Fifth Avenue with high-end boutiques, fine dining, and art galleries catering to the ultra-wealthy.  Exclusive Amenities: The town features private clubs like the Greenwich Country Club and the Belle Haven Club, which offer elite recreational facilities, including golf, tennis, and yachting. Greenwich also hosts high-profile events, such as polo matches at the Greenwich Polo Club.  Philanthropy and Culture: Wealth in Greenwich often translates to philanthropy. Residents frequently support cultural institutions like the Bruce Museum and the Greenwich International Film Festival. The town also has a robust arts scene and hosts charitable galas that attract global attention.  Education and Security: Greenwich is home to prestigious private schools, like Greenwich Academy and Brunswick School, which draw families seeking top-tier education. The town also boasts a reputation for safety and a strong sense of community.  Manhattan is the most densely populated of New York Cityâ€™s 5 boroughs. It's mostly made up of Manhattan Island, bounded by the Hudson, East and Harlem rivers. Forest Hills is a mostly residential neighborhood in the central portion of the borough of Queens in New York City. It is adjacent to Corona to the north, Rego Park and Glendale to the west, Forest Park to the south, Kew Gardens to the southeast, and Flushing Meadowsâ€“Corona Park to the east. The current name comes from the Cord Meyer Development Company, which bought 660 acres (270 ha) in central Queens in 1906 and renamed it after Forest Park. Further development came in the 1920s and 1930s with the widening of Queens Boulevard through the neighborhood, as well as the opening of the New York City Subway's Queens Boulevard Line. Forest Hills has a longstanding association with tennis: the Forest Hills Stadium hosted the U.S. Open until 1978 and the West Side Tennis Club offers grass courts for its members. The area's main commercial street, Austin Street, contains many restaurants and chain stores.  Forest Hills is located in Queens Community District 6 and its ZIP Code is 11375.It is patrolled by the New York City Police Department's 112th Precinct.   ğŸ‘‰No talking, just drivingğŸ‘‰The camera was mounted outside and you could hear the raw sounds of the City.ğŸ‘‰30-minute beautiful drive - smooth binaural sounds workout for treadmill walking, jogging, or running trainingğŸš˜  ğŸ‘‰These videos are also designed to help you pass your driving test or simply understand the traffic rules and patterns in the city or country I am filming in. The name is an acronym for "Down Under the Manhattan Bridge Overpass". Dumbo is next to the Brooklyn Bridge, and is known for its cobblestone streets, old industrial-turned-residential warehouses, and the iconic feel of an old New York City neighborhood. It's also known for its history as a working-class area where immigrants from around the world lived in small apartments and worked in offices above them.  Brooklyn Heights is a posh residential area of elegant brownstones. It's known for its tree-lined promenade along the East River, with unrivaled views of Manhattan and the Statue of Liberty. The neighborhood also attracts visitors and local families to the landscaped walkways and playgrounds of waterfront Brooklyn Bridge Park. Locals gather at the longstanding bars and restaurants along Henry Street.  Manhattan is a borough of New York City, coextensive with New York County in southeastern New York state. It's the smallest borough geographically, but the most densely populated. Manhattan is known as the symbol of New York City, and is home to many of its skyscrapers and landmarks, including Times Square and Central Park. It's also described as the cultural, financial, media, and entertainment capital of the world.

New York is the geographical and demographic center of both the Northeast megalopolis and the New York metropolitan area, the largest metropolitan area in the U.S. by both population and urban area. With more than 20.1 million people in its metropolitan statistical area and 23.5 million in its combined statistical area as of 2020, New York City is one of the world's most populous megacities. title: Driving Downtown - Bronx 4K - New York City USA
description: Driving Downtown - Bronx New York City New York USA - Episode 40. Starting Point:  https://goo.gl/maps/8gNbo8irtR82 . The Bronx is the northernmost of the five boroughs of New York City, within the U.S. state of New York.     The Bronx contains one of the five poorest Congressional Districts in the United States, the 15th, but its wide diversity also includes affluent, upper-income and middle-income neighborhoods such as Riverdale, Fieldston, Spuyten Duyvil, Schuylerville, Pelham Bay, Pelham Gardens, Morris Park and Country Club.[10][11] The Bronx, particularly the South Bronx, saw a sharp decline in population, livable housing, and the quality of life in the late 1960s and the 1970s, culminating in a wave of arson. Since then the communities have shown significant redevelopment starting in the late 1980s before picking up pace from the 1990s until today.  About a quarter of the Bronx's area is open space,[5] including Woodlawn Cemetery, Van Cortlandt Park, Pelham Bay Park, the New York Botanical Garden and the Bronx Zoo in the borough's north and center. These open spaces are situated primarily on land deliberately reserved in the late 19th century as urban development progressed north and east from Manhattan.  The name "Bronx" originated with Jonas Bronck, who established the first settlement in the area as part of the New Netherland colony in 1639.[6][7][8] The native Lenape were displaced after 1643 by settlers. In the 19th and 20th centuries, the Bronx received many immigrant groups as it was transformed into an urban community, first from various European countries (particularly Ireland, Germany and Italy) and later from the Caribbean region (particularly Puerto Rico, Jamaica and the Dominican Republic), as well as African American migrants from the southern United States.[9] This cultural mix has made the Bronx a wellspring of both Latin music and hip hop.  Revitalization In 1997, the Bronx was designated an All America City by the National Civic League, acknowledging its comeback from the decline of the mid-century.[65] In 2006, The New York Times reported that "construction cranes have become the borough's new visual metaphor, replacing the window decals of the 1980s in which pictures of potted plants and drawn curtains were placed in the windows of abandoned buildings."[66] The borough has experienced substantial new building construction since 2002. Between 2002 and June 2007, 33,687 new units of housing were built or were under way and $4.8 billion has been invested in new housing. In the first six months of 2007 alone total investment in new residential development was $965 million and 5,187 residential units were scheduled to be completed. Much of the new development is springing up in formerly vacant lots across the South Bronx.[67]  Sports The Bronx is the home of the New York Yankees of Major League Baseball.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bronx  https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attractions-g47369-Activities-Bronx_New_York.html  http://www.nycgo.com/boroughs-neighborhoods/the-bronx

title: Syracuse, New York - Driving Tour 4K
description: Syracuse (/ËˆsÉªrÉ™kjuËz, ËˆsÉ›r-, -kjuËs/ SIRR-É™-kewz, SERR-, -â kewss) is a city in and the county seat of Onondaga County, New York, United States. It is the fifth-most populous city in the state of New York following New York City, Buffalo, Yonkers, and Rochester.  At the 2020 census, the city's population was 148,620 and its metropolitan area had a population of 662,057. It is the economic and educational hub of Central New York, a region with over one million inhabitants. Syracuse is also well-provided with convention sites, with a downtown convention complex. Syracuse was named after the classical Greek city Syracuse (Siracusa in Italian), a city on the eastern coast of the Italian island of Sicily.  Historically, the city has functioned as a major crossroads over the last two centuries, first between the Erie Canal and its branch canals, then of the railway network. Today, Syracuse is at the intersection of Interstates 81 and 90. Its airport is the largest in the Central New York region.  Syracuse is home to Syracuse University, SUNY Upstate Medical University, SUNY ESF, and Le Moyne College.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syracuse,_New_York  #syracuse, #newyork, #dsnevada
